The articles below are listed in order of perceived usefulness to our project:

Articles on Institutional Bibliographies and Useful Apps

Tabaei, S., Schaffer, Y., McMurray, G., & Simon, B. (2013). Building a Faculty Publications Database: A Case Study. Public Services Quarterly, 9(3), 196-209. Available online at: http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/15228959.2013.816127
-Best article in this group
-Includes a section on faculty bibliography vs. faculty repository
-Includes useful sample criteria for inclusion (e.g. scholarly papers and creative works, but not blogs, broadcast media, or awards)

Connor, E. (2008). Using Wiki technology to build a faculty publications database. Journal of Electronic Resources in Medical Libraries, 4(4), 11-25. Available online at: http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1300/J383v04n04_02
-Wikis may be a good option if, for any reason, we decide not to use BibApp, or decide we need more flexibility than BibApp offers

Armstrong, M., & Stringfellow, J. (2012). Promoting faculty scholarship through the university author recognition bibliography at Boise State University. New Review of Academic Librarianship, 18(2), 165-175. Available online at: http://scholarworks.boisestate.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1064&context=lib_facpubs
-Offers many instances of pitfalls to avoid in setting up an institutional database


Apps:
http://bibapp.org/
-Created by LIT staff from the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and University of Wisconsin Madison specifically for building institutional bibliographies
-Open source (!)
-Offers automatic rights-checking through SHERPA/RoMEO, which would facilitate switching to a repository
-Offers customizable faculty profiles (with pictures!)
-Live install at the University of Kentucky Medical Center here: https://experts.kumc.edu/
